                            James‚ÄìThis was an incredible read. Thank you for taking the time to put it together. In running my campaign for Viticulture, I had a back-and-forth debate about the early-bird pledge level (I ended up doing it). I think you have a great point that it makes it difficult for people to change their pledge level later. I tried to alleviate that by offering the early-bird backers ways to upgrade their pledge level. In fact, that seemed to work really well since they already felt like they were getting a special deal.
I think the one element about early bird levels that I struggle with a bit is this: ‚ÄúDo not offer any special incentives to pledge right away.‚Äù From my perspective, almost everything you do on a Kickstarter page is to try to get someone to pledge right away, because once they leave that page, they may never come back. That‚Äôs why you need a polished project page, reasonable and interesting rewards, a video‚Äìall those other things you mention. I‚Äôm curious why that wouldn‚Äôt apply to pledge levels?
I‚Äôm not set on doing early birds in the future, but my experience with Viticulture indicated that people weren‚Äôt turned off at all by a $4 increase in price after the early birds ran out. That was with no established audience, so perhaps it‚Äôll be different the second time around. But I‚Äôm almost thinking that a good way to show my appreciation for my Viticulture backers would be to offer more early bird pledge levels and let those backers know about the project the second it launches. Sure, the $4 or so won‚Äôt make a big difference to them, but I wonder if the loyalty factor is worth it. What do you think?

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
									James Mathe on January 29, 2013
									                                

                                
									Reply ‚Üì                                


                            Jamey, the answer is that if you have a line of people at the door you don‚Äôt offer the first 20 discounted tickets. That‚Äôs just pissing money out the door. My point is that those 20 people will now be twice as hard to convince to change their pledge to something greater. So you hurt your campaign overall by doing an early bird limited sale. I suppose if you‚Äôre having a hard time getting traction, then you might try using one. But I would never use one the first day!

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
									Jamey Stegmaier on January 29, 2013
									                                

                                
									Reply ‚Üì                                


                            Interesting. Thanks for your response‚ÄìI like the analogy about the line of people at that door. In terms of economics, you‚Äôre completely right‚Ä¶it just wasn‚Äôt my experience with Viticulture. As I mentioned, quite a few early bird backers upgraded their pledges without leaving that pledge level. I was basically using the ‚Äúfoot in the door‚Äù technique. They said ‚Äúyes‚Äù to the game early on, and later when there were more things available to them, they had already bought into the campaign and had been actively engaged. 
I wonder if a better way to do it‚Äìespecially when you have an established backer base‚Äìis to do an early bird with a special perk but the exact same pricing as the standard game. Backers love exclusive content. How do you think that would go over?

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
									James Mathe on January 29, 2013
									                                

                                
									Reply ‚Üì                                


                            The more you do special outside the rewards the more chance you‚Äôre going to make a mistake and deliver things wrong. Have you delivered yet? I personally don‚Äôt like the nightmares of tracking all that stuff. I still think people want to sit on the early pledge which limits what and how they can upgrade their pledges. In short, they must use the manage pledge option and over pledge every time you offer them something new. Which means you also have to track it. Your campaign has a very normal curve so I don‚Äôt think you really needed to do out of the box stuff and doing so didn‚Äôt change your curve much. So who knows.

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
									Jamey Stegmaier on January 29, 2013
									                                

                                
									Reply ‚Üì                                


                            That‚Äôs a good point about the hassle of tracking and sorting. We have three different versions of the game going out, each with a different UPC. With Amazon‚Äôs fulfillment robots taking care of the gritty work of shipping everything, I‚Äôm not too worried about people getting the wrong version of the game. But I‚Äôm sure those types of errors can add up, even if it‚Äôs a small percentage of backers.
Thanks again for the entry and the feedback. I‚Äôll definitely take this into consideration for my next campaign. If you listen to today‚Äôs Funding the Dream podcast, let me know what you think (I‚Äôm Richard‚Äôs guest on that one).

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
