									Kier on January 29, 2013
									                                

                                
									Reply ‚Üì                                


                            How do you handle card game pricing? At small print runs I feel like it would be very unlikely to get your manufacturing and oversea shipping cost down to $3.00 per unit which is what you recommend as the high point in your times 5 estimate. Is this why you pointed out card game pricing separately? If so, how do you price card games?
In my initial estimates I‚Äôve got as low as $3.60 per unit at 1,500 units without shipping. I‚Äôm using irregularly shaped cards though.

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
									James Mathe on January 29, 2013
									                                

                                
									Reply ‚Üì                                


                            You can‚Äôt mix irregular shapes and small print run in the same sentence. That‚Äôs your problem. The printer is spreading that die cost ($300) to all the units. I printed a 96 card game for about $2.50 ‚Äì I also printed a 128 card game for $5. So a double deck game can go for $17.99-$27.99‚Ä¶ I get these ‚Äúranges‚Äù from the fact that I own 3 games stores and know what people expect to pay. But you can always get away with higher print costs if you‚Äôre only selling direct. The x5 number is if you wish to make any money using a Fulfillment house and Distribution. If you‚Äôre doing Kickstarter and direct sales only you make about 2-3x more money on each sale. Which case you can live with a x3 multiplier. But you‚Äôre also going to have to live with a garage full of product that may never sell though. Which case it‚Äôs time to look at dumping at Tanga.com

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
									Kier on January 29, 2013
									                                

                                
									Reply ‚Üì                                


                            Well I say irregular. They‚Äôre square cards. Not terribly irregular and I doubt that I‚Äôm the first person to make a game using square cards. That said, I get what you‚Äôre saying, it‚Äôs not likely a die that they order in bulk and keep stock on hand.
I could always up it to a print run of 3,000 but the likeliness of me moving that many copies of a game are pretty minuscule considering I‚Äôm an independent developer and this is my first game. That does knock the price down to $2.24 per unit. Without shipping at the times five price point I‚Äôm looking at $11.25 which is well under the margin but again, good luck moving 3,000 units. I might look at some granularity between 1,500 and 3,000.

                        
                    
                    


                
                
                
                        
                        
							
                        
                    
                    
                    
                        
                            
